Kotlin runs on the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) and can also be complied to JavaScript or native code

'fun' is used to declare a function
'main()' is the entry point of the program

fun main() {
    println("Hello, World!")
}

***** Variable and Data Types *****
Don't need to explicitly specify the data type of a variable (Kotlin supports type inference)

val name = "John" // String type is inferred
var age: Int = 25 // Explicitly specifying Int type

***** 'val' (Value) *****
'val' is used for immutable (read-only) variable. meaning their values cannot be changes once initialized
val pi = 3.14
// pi = 3.14159 // Error: Val cannot be reassigned

***** 'var' (Variable) *****
'var' is used for mutable variables.  meaning their values can be changed after initialization
var counter = 0
counter = 1 // Valid: var can be reassigned


***** Function *****
fun add(a: Int, b: Int): Int {
    return a + b
}



***** Classes and Objects *****
Kotlin supports object-oriented programming with classes and objects.

class Person(val name: String, var age: Int) {
    fun speak() {
        println("Hello, my name is $name")
    }
}

fun main() {
    val person = Person("Alice", 30)
    println(person.name) // Accessing property
    person.age = 31
    person.speak() // Calling method
}

